{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2017}}'''Helen Gardner''' (1878&ndash;1946) was an American art historian and educator. Her ''[[Gardner's Art Through the Ages|Art Through the Ages]]'' remains a standard text for American art history classes.
== Biography == {{Infobox person | name = Helen Gardner | birth_date = {{Birth date|1878|03|17}} | birth_place = [[Manchester, New Hampshire]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|1946|06|04|1878|03|17}} | death_place = Chicago, Illinois | nationality = American | occupation = [[Art historian]], writer | education = [[University of Chicago]] | notable_works = [[Gardner's Art Through the Ages|Art Through the Ages]] }}
Gardner was born in [[Manchester, New Hampshire]] and attended school in the [[Hyde Park, Chicago|Hyde Park]] neighborhood of Chicago. In 1901 she graduated with a degree in classics from the [[University of Chicago]].<ref> {{cite journal |last=Kader |first=Themina |year=2000 |title=The Bible of Art History: Gardner's ''Art Through the Ages'' |journal=Studies in Art Education |volume=41 |issue=2 |pages=164–177 |jstor=1320661|doi=10.2307/1320661}}</ref> After an interval as a teacher, she returned to the same university to study art history, and received a master's degree in 1918. In 1920 she began lecturing at the School of the [[Art Institute of Chicago]], where she would spend the rest of her career, with the exception of short appointments at [[UCLA]] and the University of Chicago.<ref name="Sorensen">{{cite book|url=http://arthistorians.info/gardnerh|title=Dictionary of Art Historians|last=Sorensen|first=Lee|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=|chapter=Helen Gardner|accessdate=January 16, 2009}}</ref>
In 1919, she became the head of the photograph and lantern-slides department at the Ryerson Library of the Art Institute of Chicago. The next year she started to teach an art history course at the School of the Art Institute. In 1922, she made the choice to resign her position at the library to spare more time for teaching. From the frustration of not being able to find a comprehensive textbook that had a broad enough coverage in art history, she resolved the problem by writing such book herself, which resulted in a popular art history textbook used for decades, ''Art Through the Ages''.<ref name=Britannica>{{cite web|last1=The Editors of Encyclopædia Britannica|title=Helen Gardner|url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Helen-Gardner|website=Encyclopaedia Britannica|accessdate=March 14, 2017|date=August 17, 2016}}</ref>
Her major work, ''Art Through the Ages'' (1926), was the first single-volume textbook to cover the entire range of art history from a global perspective. Frequently revised, it remains a standard textbook at American schools and universities.<ref name=ArtInstitute>{{cite web|title=Case 3: Helen Gardner|url=http://www.artic.edu/aic/collections/exhibitions/Ryerson/Making-History/3|website=The Art Institute of Chicago|accessdate=March 14, 2017|location=Chicago|date=2013}}</ref> In 1932 she also published ''Understanding the Arts'', an art appreciation text directed toward educators. For both volumes, the analytical drawings were supplied by artist [[Kathleen Blackshear]].<ref>Landauer, Susan, and Becky Reese. "Lone Star Spirits." In Patricia Trenton, ed. ''Independent Spirits: Women Painters of the American West, 1890–1945, 199–200''. Los Angeles: University of California Press, 1995, pp. 199–200.</ref> In 1936, she published a second edition of ''Art Through the Ages'', with its content expanded.<ref name=Britannica />
In 1946, aged 68, she died due to cancer. However, despite her illness before her death, she remained in advisory capacity at the Art Institute.<ref name=ArtInstitute/>
==Works== * {{cite book |title=Art through the Ages: An Introduction to Its History and Significance |location=New York |publisher=Harcourt, Brace |year=1926}} * {{cite book |title=Understanding the Arts |location=Chicago |publisher=Harcourt, Brace |year=1932}}
